  "body": " 🔎 Loop 1   This page will serve as a viewing guide for content that will be required for class on Wednesday, July 1 .    1.1 - What are differential equations?  In this section, we will learn language to describe and classify differential equations. This section satisfies module objectives 1-3.  Watch 🎥Video 1.1.1 (1:43).  Complete the ✅Checkpoint 1.1.1 .  Watch 🎥Video 1.1.2 (2:02).  Complete the ✅Checkpoint 1.1.2 .  🎯 Practice: Try finding the order of the diffential equations given in problems 1-8 in Exercises 1.1 (pg. 10).  Watch 🎥Video 1.1.3 (4:51).  Complete the ✅Checkpoint 1.1.3 .  🎯 Practice: Determine whether each of the diffential equations given in problems 1-8 in Exercises 1.1 (pg. 10) are linear.  After completing this list, you can complete problem 1 from homework 1.    1.2 - What are solutions to differential equations?  In this section, we will learn what solutions to differential equations look like. We will also learn how to verify them and check for intervals of existence. This section satisfies module objectives 4-5.  Watch 🎥Video 1.2.1 (7:46).  Complete the ✅Checkpoint 1.2.1   Watch 🎥Video 1.2.2 (4:16).  Complete the ✅Checkpoint 1.2.2   🎯 Practice: Problems 11, 13, 21, 23 in Exercises 1.1 (pg. 10).  Watch 🎥Video 1.2.3 (3:28).  Complete the ✅Checkpoint 1.3.1   Watch 🎥Video 1.2.4 (3:27).  🎯 Practice: Problems 4-8 (evens), 18, 22 in Exercises 1.2 (pg. 17).  After completing this list, you can complete problem 2 from homework 1.    1.3 - Why should I find solutions to differential equations?  In this section, we will model some simple real-world phenomena using differential equations. We will also investigate the additional context we can glean from using differential equations (as opposed to algebraic equations) in these models.  Watch 🎥Video 1.4.1 (7:38).  Complete the ✅Checkpoint 1.3.1 .  🎯 Practice: Problems 1, 3, 5, 9, 13 in Exercises 1.3 (pg. 28).  After completing this list, you can complete problem 3 from homework 1.   "
